e</i> ‘the’, of   De Heer  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Heerema","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Dutch Egbert.","West Frisian and Dutch (Groningen): patronymic from the personal name   Heer  , composed with the Frisian suffix <i>-ma</i> ‘(one of the) men of’."]},{"name":"Heeringa","meanings":["West Frisian: habitational name from any of several mansions or farms so called, for instance near Dongjum and Marssum, once inhabited by a certain <i>Heere</i> or <i>Hero</i> and his kin (see   Heer   1). It is formed with the patronymic suffix <i>-ing</i> and genitive plural ending <i>-a</i>."]},{"name":"Hehr","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Elfriede, Erhart, Horst, Milbert.","German: variant of   Heer   1 and 3, but in some instances a nickname either from <i>hëher</i> ‘jay’, or from Middle High German <i>hēr</i> ‘distinguished, proud’."]},{"name":"Heeren","meanings":["Dutch, North German, and East Frisian: patronymic from   Heer   1."]},{"name":"Hermann","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Kurt, Hans, Jurgen, Mathias, Gottlieb, Horst, Juergen, Klaus, Lorenz, Bernd, Dieter, Erwin.","German: from a personal name composed of the ancient Germanic elements <i>heri</i>, <i>hari</i> ‘army’ + <i>man</i> ‘man’. This surname is also found in France (Alsace and Lorraine), Hungary, Poland, Czechia, Slovakia, and some other European countries; see also below. Compare   Harman   5.","Jewish (Ashkenazic): adoption of German name (see 1 above). Compare   Herman  ."]},{"name":"De Heer","meanings":["Dutch: from <i>heer</i> ‘(feudal) lord, master’, with the definite article <i>de</i> ‘the’, probably applied as a nickname to someone who behaved in a lordly manner, or as a metonymic occupational name for someone in the service of a feudal lord or the like. Compare   Heer  ."]}]},{"name":"Idda","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Pet form of any of several old Germa